ously-oriented child care advice in women’s periodicals, he examines how children ultimately came to be understood by mothers—and later, by commercial actors—as consumers. From concerns about taste, to forms of discipline and punishment, to play and toys, Cook delves into the social politics of motherhood, historical anxieties about childhood, and early children’s consumer culture. An engaging read, The Moral Project of Childhood provides a rich cultural history of childhood.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aChild consumers. 0aConsumers. 0aElectronic books. 0aMotherhood. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology of Religion.2bisacsh  aAllowances.  aChildren’s Rights.  aChildren’s rooms.  aCreative Child.  aDepravity.  aDevelopmentalism.  aDiscipline.  aEmpathy.  aFeminization.  aGirlhood.  aMalleability.  aMarket Research.  aMemory.  aMoney.  aMoral architecture.  aMoral project.  aMotherhood.  aPedagogy.  aPleasure.  aPre-capitalist child.  aPredestination.  aProperty.  aProvisioning.  aPunishment.  aReward.  aSimplicity.  aSubjectivity.  aTaste.  aValue.  achild.  aconsumption.  ainteriority.  amateriality.  amorality.  amother.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2020 Englishz978311070472308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology, Education, Psychology 2020z9783110704549oZDB-23-SEW08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311072270340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479881413423Coveruhttps://www.degruyte